Basically at the point of packing where we no longer have specific labeled boxes and everything is now just “misc.” so you know we are getting close.  Today my therapist asked me about saying goodbye to Dallas in a super non-judgemental way, even though I cite it as the location as more than one of my biggest traumas to date. Thank you for showing me what my unchecked ego can look like : snobby, mean, alienating to others and ultimately isolating. Thank you for showing me what living for the expectations of others can look like : scary, stifled, and small. When I needed to heal and hide away from people, thank you for giving me a cozy apartment surrounded by trees and a quiet walking path.  When I needed to warm up go the idea of being in a community again, thank you for giving me a neighborhood of friendly shop owners, charming store fronts and yummy treats. I’m six months away from turning 35 and not many people make massive moves  like this based on dreams and desires (most people get that out of their system in their 20s it feels like). But I think since I was young I dreamt of an unconventional life and this contributes to that first little manifestation. Bye Dallas, I’ll miss taking photos in front of DIRT!

Lately I’ve been trying to live more authentically and figure out whatever it is I want to show you here. I realized last night that I don’t have to do an overhaul of my personal “brand” or “aesthetic”. I realized that lumping myself into a category is a symptom of being ✨terminally online✨ and that I don’t need to make a broad declaration about myself that I MUST 🔪 NEVER 🔪 DEVIATE 🔪 FROM 🔪 . Going to try and create for you in a vacuum of sorts. I think that I (like many other people in my profession) can get a bit rubber-necky and try to keep up with the Kardashians. I love sharing what I’m interested in but I’m sick of setting myself up for failure with new rules (“I’m only wearing neutrals” “I only show things I can link” ) and limiting myself creatively.  Anyway I thought I’d bring you an updated list of things that are currently bringing me joy and hope you find some joy too. 

🍄 this dress is from @ivycityco and I feel like a dainty cottage fairy in it. Hence the free foot content. I think a leather boot would have been cute with this dress but it’s kind of got “yes, I’m a mythical creature but I’m also doing my laundry today” energy - and I find that soothing. 

🍄 I got my second @bookofthemonth and chose The Writing Retreat which I simply did because it was the thriller category but had no idea that so many of the themes would be in line with my direct interests (witchy stuff, Victorian mansions, upstate NY, female friendship dynamics) 

🍄 @tower28beauty Tinted SPF has been a precious moist respite for my cracked winter skin .

🍄 @randilynnreedillustration YouTube channel. Wow! Such a multi talented artist in so many ways. I consume a lot of “cozy” YouTube content wherein a person narrates over beautiful footage of themselves wandering in the woods, baking, lighting candles - living a beautiful slow life. A lot of these girls do a wonderful job but sometimes feel maudlin. Randi’s videos are so moving, I cried during two of her videos last night from the sheer beauty of her perspective and nature photography.  Her “copy” (scripting?) is very emotive and beautiful yet never feels maudlin or contrived. Enjoy!

Today I met a woman who didn’t know that @anthropologie made beautiful plus size clothing and I was reminded of the bread and butter of what I do here on instagram. I worked for a long time at Anthro (almost a decade at 4 different locations in different states) and I always dreamed of the day when I could fit into their clothes. I possess so much information on fit, quality, price points, and behind the scenes info on different  retailers because of my job. I can definitely take it for granted. But today it was fun to point at my dress and say “THIS is from Anthro!” And immediately pull out my phone to show off all the new plus size arrivals and watch someone’s day go off into an entirely new direction. It’s easy for me to feel complacent when my job depends on the fluctuations of an algorithm, or likes or an entire app getting banned … when I really began creating because I wanted to joyfully share things with people who had a hard time sniffing them out. 🖤🖤🖤🖤Just wanted to share this little story that meant so much to me today.

Messy Chats!  Getting real about self expression and how we express ourselves visually AND about the perfected almost genre like performance we consume on the daily and are meant to perceive as being someone’s REAL LIFE. A lot of people in my profession align their lives with the singularity of a BRAND.
